	<li class="comment even depth-2" id="li-comment-197">
		<article id="comment-197" class="comment-body clearfix">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/84c8308c882ba2597298133c7c00becf?s=60&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-60 photo' height='60' width='60' />			
			<span class="fn">Jeff</span>			<span class="comment_date">
				April 5, 2013			</span>		
						

																		
			<div class="comment-content clearfix">
				<p>From what I&#8217;ve read this will not result in the massive improvement in their trade balance. They have no oil or natural gas reserves and must import most of their energy, particularly due to the shutdowns of nuclear reactors due to the meltdowns at Fukushima and the resultant political fallout.</p>
<p>So their cost of energy and materials will go up in nominal terms as the value of the Yen drops. It will theoretically drop labor costs, but that will be offset to an extent due to the demographics. Japan is aging rapidly and more people are dropping out of the labor force than entering it. Japan is now selling more adult diapers than baby diapers after all. They&#8217;re also rather xenophobic and there is very little immigration into Japan to help fill those labor needs.</p>
<p>Japanese will be dumping bonds &amp;/or losing purchasing power as those near zero yield bonds crash in value vs a rising interest rate. That will hammer domestic consumption. It will also hammer the holders of those bonds, such as banks, insurance companies, pension plans and retirement accounts.</p>
<p>They are insolvent and are fighting for their lives but there&#8217;s really no way out that I can see.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s not a coincidence that they&#8217;ve had 5 of their finance ministers resign in 10 years, one of whom committed suicide and another who immediately checked himself into a mental assylum due to the stress. There truly is no escape from the inevitable. This is their hail Mary pass at the endgame. They&#8217;re hoping for a miracle. The odds are far far closer to zero than their near zero interest rates. In comparison a hail Mary pass looks like a sure thing.</p>
				
				<div class="reply-container"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2013/04/japans-debt-crisis-visualized/?replytocom=197#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-197", "197", "respond", "2618")'>Reply</a></div>			</div> <!-- end comment-content-->
